column4: More than 65 million but fewer than 70 million

A blowout day yesterday, requiring only 1.285m screenings today to surpass 65m. There were 1.65m screenings on New Year's Eve day in 2022 and there hasn't been a screening number as low as 1.285m since early February this year. Stranger things have happened, but....
Oh, this one is going to be pretty close, within 500k, but I think it will do it.
with 2 days remaining - need only 3,652,627 to move into bucket 5 - which is an average of approx 1.826million a day - the dec avg to date has been 2.115 million

With two days remaining, 1.83m screenings per day required to hit 65m. It will come down to 12/31, which has historically been a relatively light travel day. Southwest being back on track may make the difference here. My forecast is down slightly to 65.1m to 65.3m for the month, but there are only two days remaining.

The numbers just updated for 12/28. With 3 days left, we require an average of 1.93m passengers per day to hit 65m for the month. My forecast is between 65.2m and 65.4m total passengers, but if there is too much slippage from the model that averages 2021 and 2019 passenger counts (adjusted by days from Christmas), we won't even hit the lower bound. Since 12/23 the slippage has been averaging about 100,000 passengers per day. Hopefully Southwest coming almost fully online tomorrow will help on the margin.
It going to be close.
The data from the 28th isn't published yet, which is strange.

Numbers aren't coming in as strong as necessary to lock in 65m. We require just under 2m passengers per day for the rest of the year to hit 65m. In 2021, on the day of week model, there were an average of 1.83m and on the days from Christmas model there were an average of 1.93m screenings. This will go down to the wire.

With 5 days remaining, we require an average of just over 2m screenings a day to hit 65m. I have two models, one of which uses the raw data from TSA that lines up day of week, and the other one that adjusts for the number of days difference from Christmas. The forecast in each model is the average of the 2021 and 2019 screenings. Since 12/17 (roughly the beginning of the Christmas / New Years travel season), the second model has fit significantly better, with an average error of 4,000 screenings per day - the average error with the unadjusted model is about 30,000 screenings a day, and the sum of squared screening errors is about one-third as large for the adjusted as the unadjusted model.
Stronger numbers yesterday puts me more towards the 65-70M bucket.

Recalibrated model to reflect days plus or minus Christmas, rather than day of week adjustment made by TSA. This makes yesterday's seemingly low number look better, but adjustments in the forecast essentially make this almost a wash compared to yesterday. Need to average just a bit under 100,000 screenings per day more than 2021 for remainder of year to hit 65m - this average has been 168,000 per day so far over the holiday period starting 12/17. Weather shouldn't factor much going forward.

Another low day yesterday and I believe travel is limited today. My model is dropping to ~66-66.5M with the updated data, and with the trend down, I'm going to go stronger towards the 60-65M bucket. I suspect today's numbers will put me pretty confident into that bucket.

Weakest screening day relative to the average of 2021 and 2019 since the beginning of November. I'm assuming this is weather related, and even with this, average screenings are running about 40,000 per day more than the 2021/2019 average.
Lots of cancelled flights today and yesterday's numbers are down to just above 2M. My model is still showing 66-67M, but all that needs is a drop of 12-16% to hit the 60-65M bucket.

Screenings yesterday just a bit behind average of 2019 and 2021, very solid given the number of flight cancellations yesterday. Time is running out for a series of days that significantly underperforms this average.

Lots of flights being cancelled, but unless the storm destroys all the airports pretty much normal operations will resume with several days left in the month. Many people will decide to just forget about traveling this year, but enough will take delays or schedule makeups to hit 65M.
Lots of flights being cancelled https://www.cnn.com/travel/article/friday-flight-cancellations/index.html. Anecdotally my in-laws have already had two different flights cancelled.

Despite the weather, number of passengers screened yesterday fell only 25,000 short of the average from 2021 and 2019. Current projection based on this average is about 65.9m passengers. Since there are only 9 days left, screenings would have to fall far short of these averages to drop below 65m.

Another blowout day for screening, exceeding both 2019 and 2021 by at least 300,000 passengers. A great deal of this is probably travelers trying to get ahead of the weather. But at this point, the number of screened passengers only has to exceed the 2021 amounts by 50,000 a day to break 65m
Polar plunge.
Lots of weather related cancellations in Denver, Seattle and on the East Coast so I'm going to drop my forecast a bit.

A very strong screening day yesterday, exceeding both 2019 and 2021 by over 200,000 passengers. At this point, even if screening totals over the next 11 days just matches the average of 2019 and 2021, we'd hit 65.5m passengers screened (and the numbers have been exceeding this in November and December). We'll get more clarity leading up to Christmas, in terms of how weather is impacting these numbers over the next few days.

Updating using yesterday's data and inclusion of a more pessimistic scenario, in which screening counts are less than the average of 2021 and 2091, rather than greater than that average, which had been overwhelming the case until a few days ago.

Updating for 12/18 numbers, which are positive for going over 65m. However, the weather forecast for the days leading up to Christmas is quite for a large swath of the country - thus backing off a bit.
Reaffirming forecast (although shifted 2 percent from upper to lower bucket) after updating for

Through 12/16, TSA has screened 33.16m passengers, with 17 days to go. A reasonably good estimate for any given day is to take the average of the 2021 and 2019 screening data. 2020, for obvious reasons, seems irrelevant. Since the beginning of November, this average has underestimated the actual 2022 screening totals by about 50,000 screenings per day. Adding in the average from 2019 and 2021 for the remaining 17 days gives a forecast of 65.87m total screenings. Adding back the 50,000 underestimate per day gets a forecast of 66.7m screenings, which would have to fall short by 100,000 per day to go under 65m screenings. This is highly unlikely as the total screenings in 2022 has fallen short by more than 50,000 screenings compared to the prior year's averages only 4 times so far in November and December and not so far in December.
Tracking nicely toward 66, but there are still lots of things that could disrupt that, even one bad day of cancellations from storms

Current daily average for December is 2,031,685 travelers. A simple extrapolation gets 62,982,242 for the month. The average including November is 2,109,426. If the running average were the average of the remaining days, we would get a monthly value of 64,303,829 for December. It is very possible that Holiday travel will add a few million travelers the total. This may be close to the boundary between bins 4 and 5.
My model is tipping over 66 now. Still lots that could happen to put it under with half of the month to go. But for leaning a bit more towards that.

7th time calculated this question yields 67,915,400.0157, down 226,286.985 from 68,141,687.0011 a week ago. Therefore, with 2.57142857 weeks remaining and a decrease per week of 226,286.985 . . . 226,286.985 x 2.57142857 = 581,880.818. Take this 581,880.818 and use it to subtract from the latest calculation of 67,915,400.0157 . . . 67,915,400.0157 - 581,880.818 = 67,333,519.2.
63.3mn (est.)

This one is going to be close to 65M and I think we'll see accuracy come down to early leanings. I'm going with the under on account of my model being slightly under 65M and pressure from COVID/RSV/Flu, which are more likely to decrease than to increase it. Weather is another factor that can decrease travel (cancelled flights and delayed flights) where there is a non-trivial chance of impact.
Looks like ~200 per day over last year which would put in around 65k. Lots can happen in a month, including a big wave that stops travel plans,
Winter := flight cancellations.

I have 5 recorded calculations so far and the average takes me around 68.6M for December, with some variance. I'm unsure if this should be adjusted upward due to the holidays. It would require just a 2% increase in trends to get into 70M territory. We need to see a 5% drop in trends to get into sub 65M territory. I had mentioned travel could increase the trends. What could decrease it is COVID cases rising, lockdowns and stringent policies, and/or also less people traveling due to a worsening economy or perception of a worsening economy.

Too close for 70M for comfort, so I leave crumbs there. Additionally, if we see COVID take serious impacts on travel this December, it's reasonable that we see at least a 5% decrease into the 60 to 65M bin, so I leave crumbs there too. I think it's more likely than not however that we see pre-pandemic levels reached or even surpassed given it has done so at times this autumn already, which would put it rather close to 70M. Just need a 1.9% increase to get there.
68 million
current monthly average (Jan-Oct) is 62.2mil

Averaging 3 of my estimates. One method I used got me close to the Superforecaster consensus regarding the question about the first COVID-19 vaccine rolling out. One method is my most reliable method (based on my guided intuition). The other forced me to group bins together and consider them as one using same intuition but not verifiably reliable.

Updated model using data through Oct 28 yields an expected value of 69,393,570. Adjusting the range of outputs for my inside view, the lower bins cannot be ruled out due to the threat of additional COVID-19 response (either personal or political). The assumption here is that things will continue to move toward normality, beating last year's number but staying below 2019. Some weight must be given to returning to 2019 levels while the possibility of rising to new highs is remotely possible as well.
Daily numbers are about 0.2m lower than 2019. If 2019 was 70.3m this reduction of 0.2m per day is 6.2m reduction leading to a forecast of 64.1m
Scenario:

While covid is less of an issue, the door is still wide open to mask mandates and lockdowns - if not in the US, then in Europe and other countries whose citizens are the tourists who go to the US. We also have monkeypox now declared a global emergency, and polio cropping up in the UK and USA.

I started of by comparison of year 2022 to years 2019 when things were normal and 2021, impacted not so much by covid. I got a gist about the difference in each month and gave greater weight to winter months (Dec 2021 vs. Dec 2019 and Jan 2022 vs. Jan 2021) where it was about 11-12 mil down. I balanced it down a bit because this year's differences are smaller throughout the year. Therefore, I think 9-11 mil. down is a fair estimate. I put greater significance to the numbers with greater differences because things might go wrong easier than going suddenly better, as this year is still behind more than 5 mil. down each month against 2019 even though the COVID cases decreased. Hence, only minuscule probabilities went for over 65 mil.

Shifting downwards overall based on a closer look at the data so far. While the easily available TSA data only starts at 2019, and so makes any modeling very difficult to take seriously, there are some general trends to take into account and a baseline provided by an ARIMA model through today.
Initial forecast, will adjust later with more concrete data.
I think the numbers will be close to 2019 (but a bit under) unless something drastic happens.
monthly avg for 2022 to date is 57-58million a month (high of 67mil, low of 40mil) - anticipate remain and current levels or increase

However, airplane travel decreases strongly among high-income group in recessions, and we should expect rich people to be at least spooked by december. I suspect many americans are too slow to adapt to their being spooked.
